[2]
Date: Wed, 2 Apr 1997 12:51:58 -0600
To: promed@usa.healthnet.org
From: "Richard E. Isaacson" <isaacson@uiuc.edu>
Subject: E. coli superbug
Regarding the apparent association of antibiotics and the production of the
SLT toxin of E. coli O157:H7, this may be the result of release due to cell
lysis; SLT=shiga-like toxin, this is the toxin that is produced by E. coli
O157:H7 and is likely the agent that causes hemolytic uremic syndrome. This
clearly would be assumed with beta lactams.
The fact that Ciprofloxacin is effective in increasing toxin might also be a
release issue. Cells treated with ciprofloxacin form long filaments and
these may be more prone to lysis. Since ciprofloxacin is an inducer of the
SOS response in E. coli, there could be increase if the toxin's promoter is
normally part of this response (or an element similarly regulated by SOS).
Richard E. Isaacson
Department of Veterinary Pathobiology
University of Illinois
